710731f-a.text:
Eleventh Avenue, north from W. 58th Street (from a point slightly to the southward of same). North of the first gas holder this thoroughfare becomes West End Avenue today (1938). The chimneys at the left are atop the power house of the I.R.T. Note the cobblestones, the street car tracks, the overhead telephone wires and the electric lamp.
December 1905.
Geo. L. Balgue

710734f-a.text:
Eleventh Ave. (right, foreground), east side, south from West 57th(left, foreground) to 56th Streets, showing the foundation of the New Sheffield Farms plant under construction. The New York Central Railroad tracks shown will be enclosed and two private sidings built for the sole service of this company. The buildings shown to the left and at the rear of this clearance will shortly be demolished and their sites added to permit this ultra modern milk plant to extend to its full length of 550 feet. The photographer is viewing in a southeastward direction to show silhouetted against the sky the 42nd Street and Times Square building outline.
1937.
Gift of New York Central System
Publicity Bureau.

710735f-a.text:
Eleventh Ave. (right, fore to background), east side, south from West 57th (center, right to left) Street, showing the new Sheffield Farms plant under construction on the westerly portion of the 57th to 56th Street block. Beneath same runs the new road bed of the New York Central Railroad which appears on the right emerging at a tangent to cross the Avenue to the 60th Street yards. The old plant to the rear of this new building will be razed and the new structure extended shortly. Two private railroad sidings service this enterprise.
July 24, 1937.
Gift of New York Central System
Publicity Bureau.
